Figure 4.1: Avg. sentence length and Avg. actual time served (Months) by state. Sentence length is he longest length of time as stated by the court that the offender could be required to serve for all offenses. Prison stints with a sentence length or time served of ‘zero’ are exluded, as are stints with proportions greater than 2. Time served is the time between date of release and date admitted plus the length of time served in jail prior to the date of admission to prison and credited to prison service for the current sentence. The dotted vertical line indicates the year TIS was introduced.

Figure 4.2: Avg. proportion of sentence served by state and year. Sentence length is he longest length of time as stated by the court that the offender could be required to serve for all offenses. Prison stints with a sentence length or time served of ‘zero’ are exluded, as are stints with proportions greater than 2. Time served is the time between date of release and date admitted plus the length of time served in jail prior to the date of admission. The dotted vertical line indicates the year TIS was introduced.

Figure 4.3: Recidivism is coded as a dummy variable equal to 1 if an individual serves another prison stint within 365 days of the previous stint ending.

Figure 4.4: Distribution of time served before and after TIS was enacted. States with only one distribution did not enact TIS. Time served is the time between date of release and date admitted plus the length of time served in jail prior to the date of admission.

Figure 4.5: Distribution of proportion served before and after TIS was enacted. States with only one distribution did not enact TIS. Sample is limited to observations where the proportion served is less than 2. Proportion served is Time served divided by the sentence length.

5 Empirical Method

6 Main Results

I use OLS to estimate @ref(eq:es_con) and @ref(:did_con), with and without controls. I estimate each equation on the full sample and separately for violent, drug, and property offenses. Because TIS laws primarily cover violent offenses, we would expect treatment effects to be absent or muted for the other types of offenses. Standard errors are clustered at the state level in all estimations (Cameron and Miller (2015); Abadie and Athey (2022)). 1 For results derived using White standard errors, refer to the appendix.
